snippet.textDisplay:
As far as contamination in food - there is an interesting article on it here, written by someone who is onvolved very much in the field and is used as an expert witness too. http://www.eureferendum.com/blogview.aspx?blogno=87019

The one paragraph summary however is that: "The difference between UK and USA levels is one of words - and not of contamination". Both places recognise food grows in a "contaminated" environment and that not all contamination can be effectively removed. The USA formally limits the levels of contamination, the eu simply does its best to keep it as low as it can".

The inference being that, in fact, although they sounds grim, the USA limits may well be more severe than what we blissfully tolerate in the EU. But because we do not even have a formal guideline which lists maximum contamination levels, then people can delude themselves that they must all be zero.

They are not.
